descript.abstract: Boundaries of the Ecological Regions of New York State, taken from Will et. al. (1982) and Dickinson (1983).
descript.purpose: A polygon data set to be used in GIS applications showing the ecological regions of New York State.
descript.supplinf:
1. In compiling a consolidated map for ecozones of New York State, John Ozard grouped 16 northern zones into three data management units labeled J, K, and L. These units were never intended to be major zones but were grouped simply to facilitate storage in a database.
2. In compiling a consolidated map for ecozones of New York State, John Ozard reconciled differences between the mappings of Will et al. and Dickinson. Additional information on the creation of a consolidated ecological zone map from the sources of Will et al. and Dickinson is available from the Habitat Inventory Unit, New York State Department of Environmental Conservation, 625 Broadway, Albany, NY 12233-4754.

srcinfo.srccontr: Digitized from the statewide mylar map according to specifications from John Ozard of the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation's Significant Habitat Unit during the mid-1980's.

procstep.procdesc: John Ozard prepared the Ecological Zones of New York State map by consolidating the two cross reference documents Physiographic Zones of Southern and Western New York, and The Ecological Zones of Northern New York.
The New York State Department of Environmental Conservation's Habitat Inventory Unit digitized the statewide mylar map Ecological Zones of New York State.

The MINOR item in the PAT was coded for polygons in the major zones F, G, H, and I (this had not been done, presumably because there are no subzones within these zones). For these polygons the alpha-numeric portion of the MINOR item was coded with the zone letter plus "01", and the proper name portion was coded the same as the major zone. The redifined item MINOR_NUM and MINOR_DESC were created to allow these two components of the MINOR item to be displayed separately. The zone coding of Governors and Roosevelt Islands were changed from Coastal Lowlands to Manhattan Hills, based on the bedrock geology (as depicted on the NYS Education Department's 1970 Geologic Map of NYS) and the zone descriptions in Dickinson 1983. These changes were completed on 8/16/96.

attr.attrdef: Major zones. Dickinson divided the southern and western part of the state into 9 major zones labeled A through I. Ozard aggregated the northern part of the state into 3 "zones" labeled J through L for data management purposes only. These 3 northern "major zones" have no ecological meaning. SEE SUPPLEMENTAL INFORMATION 1.

attrdomv.udom: This item contains the word "ZONE", a letter designation for the zone, and the major zone name for the southern and western zones derived from Dickenson.

attr.attrdef: Minor zones. Dickinson further divided the southern and western part of the state into 22 subzones. In his compilation, Ozard considered these subzones hierarchically equivalent to the 25 northern zones of Will et. al. These zones, consolidated to number 40 by Ozard, are recorded in this item. SEE SUPPLEMENTAL INFORMATION 1.

attrdomv.udom: The zone is designated by the letter of the major zone followed by a two digit number, followed by the proper name of the zone.

attr.attrdef: The zone letter designation from the item MAJOR.
The name of the zone (redefined as the 5th through the 33rd columns of MINOR).

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: The minor zone designation (redefined as the first 3 columns of MINOR).
